article.description:
Cisti Greenwalt had 21 points and 10
rebounds as No. 7 Texas Tech defeated Texas A&M 83-38 Wednesday
night.
article.headline: Greenwalt paces Texas Tech with 21 points
article.linkText: Sharp wins No. 499 in Texas Tech's rout of Aggies
article.story:
LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- When Texas Tech's starters struggled
early, Lady Raiders coach Marsha Sharp knew exactly what to do.

	   Sit the starters, and bring in the reserves.

	   (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 7 AP) Texas Tech's depth proved to be too much for Texas A&M to handle Wednesday night as the bench provided 50 points
in an 83-38 victory.

	   "I thought our players who came off the bench came out and
played hard,'' Sharp said. "They did a great job, and I was really
pleased with the effort we got out there.''

	   "That was a situation where I was not happy with the fact that
we were 1-for-6 from the floor with four turnovers. You can't win
like that, especially against the kinds of teams we're going to be playing the rest of the way.''

	   The victory was No. 499 for Sharp. She will go for No. 500 on
Saturday night at Baylor.

	   "Texas Tech has great players,'' A&M coach Peggie Gillom said.
"They took their first five out, and they've got about five more
players that can start on any team.''

	   Cisti Greenwalt provided the biggest lift for the Lady Raiders.
The sophomore post scored 21 points and pulled down 10 rebounds.

	   She scored 12 points in the first half when Tech's sluggish
offense needed a spark.

	   "We came out and didn't hit our shots,'' said Jia Perkins, who
scored all 10 of her points in the second half. "They (the second
unit) came off the bench and did a nice job, and Cisti did an
awesome job.''

	   The performance of the bench players came as no great surprise
to Sharp.

	   "We know what that group is capable of,'' Sharp said. "When
you have a great starting five and you go to the bench, the tendency is to worry about losing a lead.

	   "I don't worry about that. Many times, this group has gone in
and pushed a 20-point lead to 30 points.''

	   Jametra Clark added 11 points for Tech (20-2, 9-1 Big 12).

	   Toccara Williams and Tamea Scales had seven points apiece to
lead Texas A&M (9-12, 2-8).

	   Tech's second unit, paced by Greenwalt and guard Miklannet
Tennal, responded by scoring 10 unanswered points and turning a 4-2
deficit into a 12-4 lead.

	   "I think confidence-wise, this game will help me,'' Greenwalt
said. "I've been in a slump, really, since the last time we played
Texas A&M. I've needed to work hard, and I've been working hard on
turning and shooting. Hopefully, it will turn around.''

	   Tennal sparked the Lady Raiders with a 3-pointer at the 15:36
mark, and Clark followed with a three-point play. Greenwalt, who
finished the first half with 12 points, added a pair of layups to
cap the run.

	   Tech took command just before halftime, building a 30-16 lead
with 1:40 to go before the break.

	   Tech's starting five returned to the court at the start of the
second half and quickly produced. Perkins scored six straight
points after a pair of free throws by Tech's Plenette Pierson,
giving the Lady Raiders a 40-20 lead with 17:41 remaining.

	   The Lady Raiders continued to stretch the lead throughout the
second half.

	   Natalie Ritchie scored nine points on a pair of 3-pointers and
three free throws. Her second 3-point basket pushed Tech's lead to
55-27.

	   The win gave the Lady Raiders their 14th consecutive 20-win
season.
